The essential differences between the Carter-Penrose diagram of
the massive charged solutions and the diagram of the massive
uncharged solutions are: (1) the curvature singularity is now
represented by a timelike line rather than a spacelike line, (2)
excluding the extreme and naked cases, there are now (in addition
to the accelerated Rindler-like horizon, ) not one but two
extra horizons, the expected inner () and outer ()
horizons associated to the charged character of the solution.

The Carter-Penrose diagram of case (i) is drawn in Fig.
.(i) and has a structure that, as occurs in the massive
uncharged case, can be divided into left, middle and right
regions. The middle region contains the spacelike infinity and an
accelerated Rindler-like horizon, , that was already present
in the  corresponding diagram (see Fig. ). The
left and right regions both contain a timelike curvature
singularity (), and an inner () and an outer ()
horizons associated to the charged character of the solution. This
diagram is analogous the the one of the non-accelerated ()
dSReissner-Nordstro m solution. However, in the 
solution the cosmological and black hole horizons have the
topology of a round sphere, while in the dS C-metric ()
the presence of the acceleration induces a non-spherical shape in
the accelerated horizon (that coincides with the cosmological
horizon) and in the black hole horizons. Indeed, notice that once
we find the zero, , of  that corresponds to an
accelerated or black hole horizon, the position of these horizons
depends on the angular coordinate  since .
