 Pair of accelerated black
holes (, )  

Now, we are in a position to interpret the massive and charged
solutions that describe two black holes accelerating away from
each other. To see clearly this, let us look to the Carter-Penrose
diagrams, Fig. , Fig.  and Fig. .
Looking at these diagrams we can compare the different features
that belong to the massless uncharge case (Fig. ), to
the non-extreme massive uncharged case [Fig. .(i)], and
ending in the non-extreme massive charged case [Fig.
).(i)]. In Fig.  we identify the two
hyperbolas  (represented by two timelike lines) approaching
asymptotically the Rindler-like acceleration horizon (). When
we add a mass to the solution we conclude that each of these two
simple hyperbolas  are replaced by the more complex structure
that represents a Schwarzschild black hole with its spacelike
curvature singularity and its horizon [this is represented by
 in the left and right regions of Fig. .(i)]. So,
the two accelerating points  have been replaced by two
Schwarzschild black holes that approach asymptotically the
Rindler-like acceleration horizon [represented by  in the
middle region of Fig. .(i)]. The same interpretation
can be assigned to the massive charged solution. The two
hyperbolas  of Fig.  are replaced by two
Reissner-Nordstro m black holes [with its timelike curvature
singularity and its inner  and outer  horizons; see the
left and right regions of Fig. .(i)] that approach
asymptotically the Rindler-like acceleration horizon already
present in the  and  causal diagram. The above
discussion also applies directly to the extreme cases of the dS
C-metric.


